  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 46.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The men of the tower of Sechem. The tower of Shechem is no doubt the same fortified building as was spoken of in vers. 6 and 20 by the name of the house of Millo (see note to ver. 6). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "An",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or rather the, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "hold",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word so rendered occurs elsewhere only in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 13:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where it is rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "high places",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and is coupled with caves, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "thickets",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "rocks",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "pits",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as one of the hiding-places of the Israelites from the Philistines. It was probably some kind of keep built on an eminence, and the place where the treasure of the temple was kept (ver. 4). It appears from the narrative that the tower of Shechem, or house of Millo, was not actually part of Shechem, nor immediately contiguous, since the report of the capture of Shechem had to be carried thither. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The god Berith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It should rather be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "El-berith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the same as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Baal-berith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in ver. 4 - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "El",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e. god",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", being substituted for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Baal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Judges 9:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "When the inhabitants of the castle of Shechem (\"lords of the tower of Shechem\"  equals  \"all the house of Millo,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 9:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") heard of the fate of the town of Shechem, they betook themselves to the hold of the house (temple) of the covenant god (Baal-berith), evidently not for the purpose of defending themselves there, but to seek safety at the sanctuary of their god from fear of the vengeance of Abimelech, towards whom they also had probably acted treacherously. The meaning of the word צריח, which answers to an Arabic word signifying arx, palatium, omnis structura elatior, cannot be exactly determined, as it only occurs again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 13:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in connection with caves and clefts of the rock. According to v. 49, it had a roof which could be set on fire. The meaning \"tower\" is only a conjecture founded upon the context, and does not suit, as צריח is distinguished from מגדּל.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]